## .NET MAUI Shell Navigation with `IQueryAttributable`

### 1. Navigate with a simple string ID

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

### 2. Navigate with the full object

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), parameters);
}
```

> The `Dictionary<string, object>` overload (added in .NET 6+) lets you pass complex objects without serializing them.

### 3. Receive both on the ViewModel

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1 — simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service, etc.
        }

        // Approach 2 — full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            // use product directly
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }
}
```

### 4. Wire it up

**Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**Bind the ViewModel (via DI or directly):**
```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();

// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

### Key points

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Passed via** | URI query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` |
| **Arrives as** | `string` in the dictionary | Original CLR object |
| **Best for** | Simple IDs, deep links | In-memory navigation with rich data |

Both arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method — you just check which keys are present. The string approach also supports `[QueryProperty]` attributes, but `IQueryAttributable` gives you full control and works for both cases in one place.
